Intrusive thoughts
You know all those intrusive thoughts that you have? People without OCD have them, too. They just don’t notice them, or they notice them and think, “Wow, that was weird. Wonder what could I have for lunch today?” and go on with their life.

People with untreated OCD, however, will have an intrusive thought and think, “Wait! Why did I have that thought?That’s a horrible thought! I don’t want that! I wouldn’t do that! I wish these thoughts would go away!”

And therein lies the difference. There are no OCD thoughts. There are instead OCD reactions to intrusive thoughts.

What causes OCDis our reaction to those intrusive thoughts. Our reaction of shock, fear, horror, disgust, etc. tells our brains, “Oh! That thought is important! We need to do somethingabout it (i.e. a compulsion).”
Then we do rituals, which reinforces in our brains that the only way we survived having those thoughts was to do compulsions. So we’re going to be more motivated to do them again, which gets us stuck in the OCD cycle of hell.

In fact, once you’ve gone through ERP therapy, you’re what Jonathan Grayson describes in a recent The OCD Stories podcast as“better than normal,” because you have a black belt in managing uncertainty. With that black belt, you can manage the everyday uncertainties of life even better than people who don’t have OCD and who haven’t been through exposure therapy. You’re actually more prepared to live in our world of uncertainty and be happy anyway than “normal people” (if there even is such a thing).

It depends on what learning style works for you and keeps you motivated.

If you want to reduce friction early on I found it easy to do the "kanji first" approach (learning some 300-1000 kanji without vocab) as it made learning vocabulary later less frustrating. if you want raw efficiency most people say like 100-200 kanji and then vocabulary only. Most people take about a month or two to rote 1000 kanji, but if you're good with memory layouts (and have a lot of time) my friend did it in 2 weeks.

I prefer geographical memory paths early and then anki flashcards once every ~150 new words. I don't use anki on the first two weeks of learning new words because it's way too frustrating to throw them out of order. Don't stress too much about building a massive vocabulary, you get very far with a few thousand words.

Don't wait too long to learn basic grammar, it takes time to get used to. I ignored all moon runes when learning grammar at first so I could focus on getting used to it. Come back to grammar routinely during your first months, then start reading basic texts as soon as you can.

Prioritize sustaining your learning long-term rather than the fastest possible method short-term, but make sure you keep challenging yourself.
